				<outline text="a #toolsforthought use case.

If you use an outliner and write code, you should try writing code in the outliner. 

Here's an example, a full web server in JavaScript in an outliner.

https://t.co/7KGiNB1jbm" type="tweet" created="Thu, 01 Jul 2021 14:16:30 GMT" tweetId="1410603220930494466" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1410603220930494466" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="The big win is you can organize your code in an outline the way it is organized in the programming language. 

So you can move functions around by dragging their top headline, and dropping it where you want it." type="tweet" created="Thu, 01 Jul 2021 14:16:30 GMT" tweetId="1410603222226505746" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1410603222226505746" inReplyToId="1410603220930494466" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="There's no limit to the size of comments, because they remain collapsed until you expand them.

I find the change notes at the top of a long-lived function are like a blog. 

When you turn a headline into a comment, everything subordinate is treated as a comment." type="tweet" created="Thu, 01 Jul 2021 14:16:30 GMT" tweetId="1410603223384170496" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1410603223384170496" inReplyToId="1410603222226505746" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
