					<outline text="A quick search reveals that the author of the song was a slave-holder, and the &quot;land of the free&quot; part is an insult to black Americans whose ancestors were most certainly not free. Also Francis Scott Keys was himself a slave holder.

https://t.co/ugDFPtRP9m" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 16:29:05 GMT" tweetId="1409549423147900928" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409549423147900928" inReplyToId="1409547563217326083" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="Repubs make fun of being &quot;woke&quot; but there's nothing wrong with waking up to how it would feel to see the acceptance of slavery in our country's legacy." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 16:34:58 GMT" tweetId="1409550902772613127" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409550902772613127" inReplyToId="1409549423147900928" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
							<outline text="When I visited Berlin, for example, I didn't see statues of  Nazi leaders. They didn't hide the history, but everywhere they made it clear &quot;this is not who we are now.&quot;" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 16:34:58 GMT" tweetId="1409550903833772044" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409550903833772044" inReplyToId="1409550902772613127" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
								<outline text="The US should review our legacy from the point of view that black people are full citizens of this country, and as entitled to the respect of the country as anyone else. 

We're just starting to look at this now, 156 years after abolition. 

https://t.co/2deOaDi99t" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 16:34:58 GMT" tweetId="1409550904819433474" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409550904819433474" inReplyToId="1409550903833772044" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
								</outline>
							</outline>
						</outline>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Congrats to Dennis Crowley after 12 years at Four Square he's moving on.  https://t.co/X29UGHs1xs" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:23:07 GMT" tweetId="1409517725463031808" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409517725463031808" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
				<outline text="1/2 There should be a limit on the number of times a team can foul one player. When a team exceeds the limit, the team being fouled gets to choose a player on the fouling team who is fouled out of the game. Do it again, lose another player." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:21:45 GMT" tweetId="1409517377654603782" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409517377654603782" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="2/2 Hack-A-Shaq isn't good for the game. There's no reason a power dunker like Giannis has to be a good foul shooter." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:21:49 GMT" tweetId="1409517394280783873" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409517394280783873" inReplyToId="1409517377654603782" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
					</outline>
				<outline text="1/9 It's kind of a shame Apple didn't do something creative with their pricing for podcasts." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:30 GMT" tweetId="1409514548357386240" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514548357386240" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="2/9 First, pricing for podcasts, as they have implemented it, is awkward and confusing, as evidenced by the way NPR did it. The pricing is voluntary, according to their press release. You can still listen if you don't subscribe (for money). Not sure how it could work otherwise." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:34 GMT" tweetId="1409514565000368129" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514565000368129" inReplyToId="1409514548357386240" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="3/9 Would NPR want to transition Fresh Air, one of the founding podcasts?" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:38 GMT" tweetId="1409514581781778442" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514581781778442" inReplyToId="1409514565000368129" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
							<outline text="4/9 But, what if there were something new, call it a &amp;lt;i&amp;gt;paycast&amp;lt;/i&amp;gt; perhaps, where you pay per episode. Maybe $1 per. Flat price, everything costs the same, at least at first. Keep it simple and easy to understand." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:42 GMT" tweetId="1409514599385346053" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514599385346053" inReplyToId="1409514581781778442" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
								<outline text="5/9 You need a special app so there's no confusion about what's what." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:46 GMT" tweetId="1409514616250634240" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514616250634240" inReplyToId="1409514599385346053" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
									<outline text="6/9 It's tied to your credit card. Every time you listen to at least 5 minutes of a podcast, you pay. Put a warning beep at 4 minutes 45 seconds." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:50 GMT" tweetId="1409514633925365763" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514633925365763" inReplyToId="1409514616250634240" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
										<outline text="7/9 I would love to try this out because I'm pretty sure this is the way web news will ultimately work, and there is no pricing model for podcasts, therefore nothing to displace, unless you consider ads a model, see below. As long as we're trying something new, might as well try" type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:10:55 GMT" tweetId="1409514654032932865" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514654032932865" inReplyToId="1409514633925365763" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
											<outline text="8/9 something better than what's already out there, from the point of view of users (we're the ones with your money in our pockets)." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:11:01 GMT" tweetId="1409514676598226945" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514676598226945" inReplyToId="1409514654032932865" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
												<outline text="9/9 And btw, no ads please. Ads in podcasts really suck, esp the ones at the beginning. I almost never make it through the ads." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 14:11:05 GMT" tweetId="1409514695363645443" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409514695363645443" inReplyToId="1409514676598226945" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
												</outline>
											</outline>
										</outline>
									</outline>
								</outline>
							</outline>
						</outline>
					</outline>
				<outline text="A #toolsforthought story, should work in any outliner.

1. I start my programming day with a new outline entry where I make notes about the first projects I'm going to do Inevitably, I think of next steps, so I note them too." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 13:35:07 GMT" tweetId="1409505644374368256" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409505644374368256" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="2. At the end of the day, I make notes for the next day, so I never have to worry about showing up to work and having no idea of what I'm supposed to do (this happens sometimes)." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 13:35:07 GMT" tweetId="1409505645280251905" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409505645280251905" inReplyToId="1409505644374368256" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="3. In the middle, I note anything I might need to remember about the work in the future, similar to the way a doctor takes notes on your chart as they do an exam, or decide on a plan." type="tweet" created="Mon, 28 Jun 2021 13:35:08 GMT" tweetId="1409505646261714949" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409505646261714949" inReplyToId="1409505645280251905" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
						</outline>
					</outline>
