				<outline text="There's a difference in trying to trick a computer into doing your thinking, and using a tool that helps organize your thinking so it's more useful to you.

#toolsforthought" type="tweet" created="Sun, 27 Jun 2021 17:54:15 GMT" tweetId="1409208468226121728" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409208468226121728" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
				<outline text="I used to read biographies as a kid, loved reading the stories of great people. 

Now I have trouble getting through them, because I know the truth and the stories in the biographies are not that. 

As a kid I reveled in gullibility." type="tweet" created="Sun, 27 Jun 2021 17:43:02 GMT" tweetId="1409205645237161988" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409205645237161988" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
				<outline text="A slogan for programmers. &quot;Let's see what happens.&quot; 

An idea pops into your head. I wonder if that could possibly work? Go for it." type="tweet" created="Sun, 27 Jun 2021 17:27:57 GMT" tweetId="1409201851011063812" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409201851011063812" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
					<outline text="Other kinds of product designers, engineers, or screen writers, don't have the luxury we have. Usually we can try something out and see what happens, and if it blows up, you can shrug and say well I guess it doesn't work. Or maybe it does." type="tweet" created="Sun, 27 Jun 2021 17:27:57 GMT" tweetId="1409201851782815745" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409201851782815745" inReplyToId="1409201851011063812" tweetUserName="davewiner" >
						<outline text="Or maybe in its failure it'll give you and idea of what might work. But be careful not to risk actual data." type="tweet" created="Sun, 27 Jun 2021 17:27:58 GMT" tweetId="1409201852814708743" urltweet="https://twitter.com/davewiner/status/1409201852814708743" inReplyToId="1409201851782815745" tweetUserName="davewiner" />
						</outline>
					</outline>
